content.description: Crux is in the middle, thin feet, tiny crimp pockets.
pockets through an overhang
content.location: Located to the right of Sabie's Eight 5.9

content.description:
This climb doesn't get any stars in the guidebook and also states that it would be a nightmare to fall before the second bolt. I would disagree with both.

If the rock were a little more solid near the first bolt, then I would give it even another star.

The start is pretty casual and leads to a long, but not too hard pull, to get to the second bolt.

Getting to the third bolt is one of the funniest moves on the entire climb. A dynamic move off a small crimper/pocket to a jug pocket.

The whole climb is quite steep and the feet are poor when you near the anchors which are quite a thrill to clip if you're pumped.
content.location: 3rd route from the left side of Pocket Rocks.

content.description: Start up on pockets and a few horizontal edges. Don't fall clipping the second bolt, then continue up past the third bolt where the terrain gets a bit steeper and the pockets become fewer and farther apart.
content.location:
Near the east (right) side, where the trail arrives at

Pocket Rocks

. Starts on a ledge above the level of the trail (unlike the topo photo in

Rock Climbs of Southwest Utah & The Arizona Strip, Second Edition

, which shows it starting at the trail level).

content.description: Steep start to good edges.  Great top rope, just extended the anchor at the top to reduce drag.
content.protection: Long runners to extended the top rope from the chains.  You can climb the love pinnacle 5.8 to set up a top rope or go around
content.location: This is the first route you see when you get off the trail on the way to the pocket rocks.

content.description: Vertical to slightly overhung line with pockets and crimps.
content.location: Right of the pocket route.

content.description: Scramble to the top of a small pillar to gain access to the route. Clip 1st bolt before pulling into the shallow dihedral. Route moves up the face on excellent pockets. Great route that doesn't have a hard crux move, but is sustained to the top.
content.location: Middle route on the large face(left of mustache mayhem) in the center of the formation.

content.description:
Starts out on a good pocket that you can clip the first bolt from, the hands are good through the first couple moves but the feet become kinda sparse.

When you get on top of the ledge you will want to clip the higher bolt to protect the crux, and avoid hitting the ledge, but a lower bolt was added to help out some of the shorter climbers.

The top section is really good climbing with a couple big reaches, surprisingly enough you might start to feel a little pump even though it doesnÂ’t look very steep.

You will find good pockets and ledges to clip on throughout the whole route.
content.location: To the right of Pocket Route and Renacuajo. (just around the corner)

content.description: Tricky start to nice small Pockets.  The route eases up after the second bolt but still keeps you on your toes.
content.protection: 5 bolts to chains.  Shares anchor with Carnivorous Bitch
content.location: to the right of Carnivorous Bitch

content.description: At the far end of the crag (west) lies a big, wide chimney. There is a route on its right flanks. Crisp crimps and long reaches make up this route. It seems if you were to fall you might smack the wall behind, but you don't.
content.location: Far west side of the crag; look for a wide chimney of sorts with a bolted route on its right-hand side.

content.description: Start up a steeper section on pockets and small edges for feet, with a strenuous second clip. Thereafter the angle continues easing. After the fifth bolt the top really rounds back and it's an easy walk to the anchors.
content.location:
Near the east (right) side, where the trail arrives at

Pocket Rocks

. On an east-facing aspect, to the left of

Sabie's Eight

, this route isn't in the

Goss guide

. Starts on the same ledge as

Sabie's Eight

.

content.description:
This is the small pinnacle you first come to when you get to Pocket Rocks.

It's listed as letter O and a toprope in Goss's guide.

It starts off thru a burly little steep section up to a tricky little ending.
content.protection:
3 bolts plus anchors.

You're going to need a couple of 2' slings for the anchors, if you're going to toprope the climb.
content.location:
First thing you get to at Pocket Rocks.

Descent: Walk off the back.

content.description:
This route climbs a left angling line on the far left side of Pocket Rocks.

You start a little to the left of the first bolt, you can avoid the wall to your left, but it doesn't up the grade of the route.

Pretty good pockets on a slightly overhanging rock lead to a steeper overhang thru quite a sequential series of big moves on OK pockets and flat edges.

If you fall right before the 4th bolt, which is a real possibility, it could be a pretty sweet fall.

The top, which looks burly from the ground, turns out to be fun and quite a bit easier than any of the climbing you have done so far.
content.location: Farthest left route at Pocket Rocks.

content.description:
This route climbs up crack with plenty of face holds and gear placement options.  After 15-20ft there is a ledge and the climb then continues up the hand sized parallel dihedral crack to the top

(great #9 and #10 hex placements).
content.protection:
Pro:Small to 3" gear

Gear anchor in horizontal crack at the top of the route.

Walk off east.
content.location:
This route is the crack located about 10ft left of Chips Crack.

Walk off to the East.

content.description:
I thought that this climb had a lot going for it.

A fairly easy start leads to classic Pocket Rocks pocket-pulling. There are a few cruxes in the first half, but they are easy to figure out and execute.

About halfway up the angle steepens and the rock gets more condense. You get to grab a mono, that's right a mono on a 5.10a, turn it, and do a long reach to a good little jug.

It's not over yet, the pump could start to creep up on a climber, and the ending could be a small fight to get to a clipping jug for the chains.

The bolts seemed to be perfectly spaced with no, crap your pants, sections.
content.location: A little over halfway across Pocket Rocks, this is on a small south-facing spire-like formation. And at the moment, it is the 4th route from the left side of the crag.

content.description: Easy edges and pockets, up straight-forward slab/almost vertical rock.
content.location: To the right of "Surmounting the Sumo," hike/scramble up a narrow channel for about 50 ft. The channel will open up on your left and you will be at the base of the route. The route is located on the right of a ~30' tall wall. To the right of "2-fer." Great route for beginners!

content.description:
Climb up splitter crack and face holds to chain anchors.

The route isn't climbed much, but is pretty clean.

Great stances to place from.
content.protection: Nuts and Medium cams to #2 camalot are useful.
content.location:
20' East of Mustache Mayhem.  Start up the face until you reach the crack and place nut and then continue up the crack to the top.

Rap the route.

content.description:
Many climbers want to get on this one for the name alone.

This route is tucked away in a small alcove surrounded by cedar trees. It faces west and has a couple of cruxy sections.

It's all about the feet on this one. The holds for the hands are there, but just barely for the grade.

A couple of slight bulges where you zag a little to the right and a little to the left.

Finally a bit of a run to the anchors, but the climbing here eases off and you get to enjoy all that you just got through.

Definitely not a gimme for the grade, you are going to have to fight for this one if its at your limit, maybe even if its not at your limit. :)
content.location: This is to the right of Crunch Boy up in an alcove slightly off the main trail and faces west unlike most of the other climbs at Pocket Rocks. Doesn't get any sun until mid-day. Just to the left of a Cedar Tree.

content.description: small pockets and edges

climbs.name: A day in the life of Rommstein

content.description:
Starts out with fun roof moves Crux is pulling onto the short face above the roof. A large ledge offers a great rest after the roof before tackling the pocketed face. The redpoint crux comes about two thirds of the way up when you must pull off of much small edges rather than the deep pockets. The edges are good they just feel bad compared to the pockets.

The rock quality on the short face just above the roof is a bit poor but will clean up nicely with a bit of traffic.
content.location: Located just left of Pocket Route. Starts in the obvious 2 finger pocket at the base of the roof.

content.description:
Trends right from the middle of the wall through pockets on vertical rock, slabbing out on top. Mini-crux at transition from vertical to slab; can be tricky for some.

Once led and cleaned, the fall line of the rope creates a TR variant (5.7) which climbs up the center of the wall on a blocky left facing flake surrounded by more pockets.

Two routes in one: A 2-fer!
content.location: To the right of "Surmounting the Sumo," hike/scramble up a narrow channel for about 50 ft. The channel will open up on your left and you will be at the base of the route. The route is located in the middle of a ~30' tall wall. Great route for beginners!

content.description: Start up using either only pockets, or more naturally (and more fun) stem your way to the first bolt. Continue on a number of large pockets, with the occasional smaller pocket and edge needed. After the fourth bolt the pockets mostly disappear leaving small edges on which to get to a rounded ledge. After the ledge, a move or two up steeper terrain puts you at the chains (don't fall after the ledgeâ€”it'd be a bad thing).
content.location:
Immediately obvious where the trail arrives at

Pocket Rocks

, the route climbs a relatively narrow-looking, rounded tower-like structure, to the left of a chimney with a collection of sticks in it a ways up (looks sort of like a nest). The route to the right (

More Bolts

) has a weird, homemade-looking hanger on the first bolt.
